{"id":709783,"guid":"FC8A3196496F44DCA5F314328FA804DD","previous_id":null,"previous_guid":null,"modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"8F17840EA2434B1DB0F95DD8477DC2E1","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"5113E48A3DF24BEFA0CD1882BD67A737","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Remove contaminated clothing, including any leather items such as watch bands or belts. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709784,"guid":"FA0573F52FB8428A9198D5A3E1759B63","previous_id":709783,"previous_guid":"FC8A3196496F44DCA5F314328FA804DD","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E8C6CC611BBB4426B7E24E488EBD945E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"7D57BBD539D64A5B82324FBED13C2A82","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Put on safety glasses and silver shield gloves (but don\u2019t put on the gloves if you are treating yourself and your hands are contaminated with phenol). <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709785,"guid":"EE0C5A4DF69F475F8B97385013A25484","previous_id":709784,"previous_guid":"FA0573F52FB8428A9198D5A3E1759B63","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"7AFA9862219A4957A60DBB791C384139","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"DDA7CF03733346F49C3BB47BE90DD162","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Open up a few packages of gauze pads. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709786,"guid":"E8AD787809EF4393830C0652106144CF","previous_id":709785,"previous_guid":"EE0C5A4DF69F475F8B97385013A25484","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"3D98B84FACE7438EB159F3007117624E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"95D1444EB4A14CB99BDDD1650B794483","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Pour polyethylene glycol liberally on to one of the gauze pads. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709787,"guid":"A3E12D3A10F94B0E9EA501E2CB3A6A1C","previous_id":709786,"previous_guid":"E8AD787809EF4393830C0652106144CF","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"0D06C3645D8744C4B88D7CDD578378FA","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"1581F2521782474A9E2F5046B52A1A11","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Gently wipe off excessive phenol on exposed area. Discard the gauze pad in the small plastic bag in the kit. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709788,"guid":"2D5D3A89E22A45568F8F5374CDB865D4","previous_id":709787,"previous_guid":"A3E12D3A10F94B0E9EA501E2CB3A6A1C","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2DEFAD77F3154E38BFD88417964C9DA2","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"CE1CD614D55A413EB7E97DA057D692B2","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"> Take a new gauze pad, add polyethylene glycol, and continue to clean off exposed area. Discard the pad. Repeat with a new gauze pad and application of polyethylene glycol until all visible traces of phenol have been removed from the skin. \n <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709789,"guid":"0A41A9A2009342A4890DFFB5026F5CFC","previous_id":709788,"previous_guid":"2D5D3A89E22A45568F8F5374CDB865D4","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"06C6F2E34225447485586CEB1E374B29","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"E031252A025A4AA7B7CB5998B16891EB","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Continue to gently wipe skin (do not scrape or irritate the effected skin area) with polyethylene glycol soaked gauze pads until no odor of phenol remains, changing the gauze pad frequently. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709790,"guid":"8A9561FD8D674EBF8FE6A9733F3F9924","previous_id":709789,"previous_guid":"0A41A9A2009342A4890DFFB5026F5CFC","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"1B1A44422C6C4188A65DBE76C56BBFB3","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"C4B8435D74584823BF3A6DD3F7A5479C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"> Follow-up:  Even if you feel it unnecessary call 112 or 155 and get emergency help for evaluation to determine if follow-up treatment is necessary. Don\u2019t forget to fill out an accident report!<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709791,"guid":"717DAD5F991547DF967586A7F87C6163","previous_id":709790,"previous_guid":"8A9561FD8D674EBF8FE6A9733F3F9924","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"C6B19118997A4F92BF0350C561414ADF","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"0F1C2F8A615340B386A79C521C1A7B7E","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Double bag any contaminated clothing. Label both the bag and the small zip-lock bag used to collect the used gauze wipes as \u201cHazardous Waste \u2013 Phenol Contamination\u201d.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":709792,"guid":"3FB9DA0B8812476A9DC4D530A905014C","previous_id":709791,"previous_guid":"717DAD5F991547DF967586A7F87C6163","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"FC218DAA69114396BDD8DF893DC08573","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Instructions Phenol Skin (Dermal) Exposure First Aid"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"DFBE46F3D31048BA96294057A5D2B36C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Replace the contents of the kit with new, unused items.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><span>   Phenol is a common chemical used for activities such as DNA\/RNA extraction. Phenol can be a component in a commercial reagent (e.g. QIAzol, TRIzol) or prepared as part of a mixture in the laboratory (e.g. chloroform:phenol). Because phenol solutions are an integral part of routine life science applications, their hazards may be taken for granted. Phenol can be <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">very dangerous<\/span><span> and the hazards are not just those of a typical corrosive. The hazards of phenol are 2 fold. It is both a <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">corrosive<\/span><span>(can cause severe burns) and <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">toxic<\/span><span>(absorbed phenol acts as a systemic toxin). In one case, death resulted from ingestion of as little as 15 mL. Liquid phenol can penetrate the skin with efficiency approximately equal to that of inhalation. <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Deaths have been reported for exposures of 25% or more of body surface area. Phenol has an anesthetic effect and can cause severe burns that may not be immediately painful or visible<\/span><span>. The threshold concentration of human skin damage from phenol is 1.5%. It can cause permanent <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">eye injury and blindness.<\/span><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">    Regarding first aid for dermal (skin) exposures, recommendations are that use polyethylene glycol 300 or 400 (PEG-300 or PEG-400), rather than water, for immediate first aid treatment of dermal exposures. In addition, all laboratory group members should take the need for appropriate personal protective equipment seriously and require its use as part of the laboratory's standard operating procedures.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">   For phenol spill on a floor or bench (non-body case) use an absorbent (for ex. Vermiculite). After it soaks the liquid collect them into plastic bag and store together with other toxic\/phenol waste bellow the fume hood in a ventilated cabinet.<\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1599659248}